Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string ID vs full object**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs (source page VM)

// Approach A: pass primitive query parameter
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach B: pass the full object via dictionary
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", product }
});
```

**3. Receive on the target ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product? _product;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private string? _productId;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: primitive string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            ProductId = idObj?.ToString();
            // Load product from service using the ID
            _ = LoadProductAsync(ProductId!);
        }

        // Approach B: full object (passed via dictionary overload)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var productObj) && productObj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
        }
    }

    private async Task LoadProductAsync(string id)
    {
        Product = await _productService.GetByIdAsync(id);
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigation call** | `GoToAsync($"...?key={val}")` | `GoToAsync("...", dictionary)` |
| **Received as** | `string` (boxed as `object`) | Original `Product` type |
| **URI-safe** | Yes | No — requires the dictionary overload |
| **Back-navigation friendly** | Yes (survives serialization) | No (object ref may be lost on back) |

Use **Approach A** when you have a simple identifier and want deep-link support. Use **Approach B** when you already have the object in memory and want to avoid a redundant fetch.
